We recently connected with a foster mom who was looking to receive support from C127. She is a single foster mom with three children - ages two, six, and nine. The six year old and the nine year old are sisters who have a brother, but he was separated from them in the foster system. The girls really wanted to go to church, but Mom didn't have a church she attended. 

We invited them to our church and said it would be great because the teacher for the 6-year old is also a foster parent. Turns out, that mom is actually a first-time foster parent of their 2 year old brother! They came and the girls were overjoyed, getting their faces painted and playing in bounce houses together! They were able to make memories and spent quality time together. It is such a blessing to see God’s plan being fulfilled though loving and supporting foster families.

We were recently made aware of a Care Community that surrounded a grandmother caring for her grandson via kinship care. Shortly after attending our clinic, a Columbus, IN church was eager to launch it's first Care Community. At the Launch, the team learned they would be loving on three special people in the home - Great Grandmother, Grandmother, and Grandson. However, the day before the scheduled Meet & Greet, the grandson, home alone with his great grandmother, discovered that she had passed away. That evening, the Team Leader, having never met them, went to their home to sit with them in their grief. There she learned how she and the team could best serve them during their time of loss, and the team immediately took action. Perfect strangers, now community. Furthermore, nobody could've imagined the heartache Grandma and her sweet boy would endure again, when just a few months later the grandmother's fiance passed away only weeks after being diagnosed with cancer.

When our advocates recently heard a portion of their story during the lunch panel at our February clinic, there was not a dry eye in the room. To listen to the family, the Team Leader, and the Care Community Coordinator share about the love and beautiful bond that has developed in their time of such grief and deep pain was so powerful. Grandma recently made soup and delivered it to her Team Leader during an illness, because she's "nicer now" (her words, not ours - HA!), and she feels compelled each day to serve those around her because she has been served so well. The young boy is doing far better in school, and loves when his Child Mentors pick him up from school each week to tutor and spend quality time with him. Grandma said she looks forward to those afternoons as well, because, well, a cup of coffee in peace. Perhaps the best part? She and her sweet boy are now regularly attending church, and he insists that the Care Community sit in the same row as them - "together, as family", he says. 

Strangers, then Community, now Family. "Forever", they say...

Testimonial from Michelle S, “In July of this year I was blessed with my five of my precious
grandchildren. I was not given the resources to help care for them however, and I am a veteran on a fixed
income. FAM has been absolutely amazing. I have never felt so blessed in my entire life. They have
helped with food, clothes, and other needs for the kids. One volunteer completely blew me away when
the offered to purchase a bedroom set for the kids, I was so thankful that I cried in my car for 30 minutes.
They are currently helping with repairs for my home study as well. 2 of my grand daughters are older and
have been through quite a bit, and started coming to church with me earlier this year. Them seeing this
level of care and compassion has been very good for them, and has helped to break down some of their
negativity. The younger kids don’t really understand what is going on, they just know that they are fed,
clothed, and well loved. I can’t really say what has been the most helpful thing, all I can say is I would not
be able to do this without them! I would like to thank all of the volunteers at FAM for their kindness and
generosity. You have shown me love like I have never seen before and I am so very thankful for each of
you. I pray that one day I am able to return the blessings that you have given to me to others who need
them. Thank you sincerely from me and my babies!!” (10/17/19).

July 2020 Impact Story - Agape-Live the Promise, Montgomery, AL
Shared by Cindy Harris, written by Rachel Wages

Montgomery, Alabama is a revolving door for many military families. They move in and out on a yearly basis in what has become their life’s pattern of service to our country. Many of these military families join local churches in order to provide a semblance of stability and normalcy for their children. They jump in and form new relationships with an ease of practiced skill, knowing that time is ticking if they want to make new friends. 

Last summer one such new military family moved to Alabama from New Jersey. They joined the Vaughn Forest Baptist Church as they settled into their new life in Montgomery. While in New Jersey, they had been trying to adopt a sibling group of three boys (8, 10, 11). However, the adoption hadn’t been finalized before their move. The two states didn’t work easily together and as of January, they still hadn’t had their Alabama Child Welfare/Adoption training. They were scheduled to transfer to another state by June of 2020. If the adoption wasn’t finalized by then, they would yet again be faced with starting the process over. 

This is where Live the Promise stepped in. Vaughn Forest Baptist Church has a vibrant FAM with communities of care ready to serve foster and adoptive families. This new family asked for a community of care to come alongside them in prayer. They didn’t need the other aspects of service - just prayer. Mighty, powerful, and sustaining prayer. Vaughn Forest gathered a group of volunteers to fulfill this request. They prayed and walked alongside this family through their journey.

The three boys were facing anxiety and had experienced various traumas in their young lives. They were facing an unknown future made less certain with the onset of COVID-19. However, even in the midst of a global pandemic, God heard the prayers and He answered. He sped the adoption process and paved the way for the adoption to be finalized. The caseworker came to their home to conduct the training and complete the necessary steps. The boys’ adoption was finalized on June 16, and the movers came to pack the house the next day. Six days later they moved out of state with their family cemented as a forever family. The care community at Vaughn Forest and this family were blessed to witness the hand of God moving the process of adoption forward while almost everything else in the world had come to a screeching halt. In this case, the true impact was felt by everyone involved.

We have been blown away with what God has done in the past year. We did our first care community group in September 2018 to see how it worked and get our feet wet. After that, we got approval from our pastor to present the foster ministry to some Bible Fellowship classes and see what happened. We began with the hope of forming 2 care communities in 2019 and spreading the gospel through fellowship and support of our community. God's church responded to the need in our community and we trained almost 100 volunteers in 2019 and connected with multiple foster families (all outside of our church).  In 2019 we had 8 care communities form, and by the end of 2019, 3 foster families (2 of which were un-churched) were regularly attending church. We had the honor of connecting with a family in April of 2019 to form a care community around them. They were fostering a sibling group of 3 and not involved in church anywhere. Around October of 2019 they began attending church regularly, and in February of 2020 one of the precious children accepted Jesus as Savior. We had the privilege of also celebrating with them as they were officially adopted in February 2020 and throwing them a great Adoption celebration.  Five care communities have continued to faithfully serve, even among their own hardship, through this pandemic. We have seen another precious child of one of the foster families attending  church accept Jesus as Savior a few weeks ago! We are excited to see the heart for children in foster care growing among believers and praying it keeps spreading through the body to transform our church.  The first family that started in a care community at the beginning of last year (2019), just got approved to foster this week (9/2020)!
Navigating how to spread and grow awareness during this pandemic and continue to engage our members.

Amazing how God provided through the foster parents and their care support group during sheltering at home (despite of). Foster parents felt well-supported during a difficult time and foster kids were taken care of, even if it meant for our single foster parent to use all her vacation due to foster child sickness or lack of normal daycare or childcare. What a display of God’s love and sacrificial love! It’s a blessing to see how the foster moms minister not only to the foster child but to the biological moms as well, especially during birthdays and holidays. I have also seen former foster (local) teen come back/by to visit and stay connected to their KCP Ex-foster moms. So proud and in awe of how God orchestrated those lasting bonds, restorations of trusting relationships,  and connections.

Our current two foster families have a sibling set of two. The two sisters had to be separated earlier in the year. Cheyenne has one sister and the Fishers have the younger sister. Recently, TPR was granted and the girls are legally available for adoption. The Fishers have planned to adopt the younger sister who they currently foster. They cannot take on the needs of both sisters. Both foster parents believe that the girls do better living apart as well. Counselors and teachers agree with the foster parents. DFCS has reported they agree as well and are pursuing an adoption separation waiver. CFC is praying for a family to step up and adopt the older sister. We are hopeful it can be a family in the church or at least a local family. We desire to see the sisters live as close as possible to maintain their sibling relationship.

Everyday and all day the Lord continues to sustain our foster families as they encounter new behaviors and trauma in the girls'. The Lord has grown our families and foster children in big ways this year. Glory be to God!

CFC recently suffered a great tragedy. The Rizner's two month old (Charlotte) died about a month ago. The Rizner's are Cheyenne's care team leaders. While we know and have confidence their sweet baby is with the Lord, it has been a great reminder to all of us that our children are not our own. Our children are the Lord's. Our children are on loan to us to steward and bring up in the ways of the Lord. We hurt for our Rizner's deeply. We all miss Charlotte very much too. The Rizner's faith has shined very bright this past month and they are taking a day at a time. Prayers for the Rizners and CFC. Prayer that the Rizner's will continue to seek Christ as their comfort and peace. Prayer that CFC will continue to surround the Rizner's with love and support.
